  "description": [
    "Friday July 24 1953 The President and Civil Rights By Grace Jan Waldman Copyright 1953 Jewish Telegraphic Agency Inc WASHINGTON President Eisenhowers profes sed opposition to discrimination against minorities has brought no concrete results according to the record of the new administrations promises and performance at the end of this first session of Con gress Some generalities on civil rights were recently rephrased by Eisenhower in a letter to Rep Adam Clayton Powell DNY Eisenhower wrote I shall con tinue to devote my earnest efforts to adyance both the spirit as well as the fact of equality The President explained his reluctance to act by stating As you are so well aware this problem cannot be solved wholly with either laws or directives The spirit of these objectives cannot be achieved as a result of the action of any one person no matter with how much authority and forthrightness he acte Eisenhower asserts that dis crimination segregation and pre judice are morally wrong al though he is apparently reluctant to using his executive powers to combat these evils No hearings have been held no steps have been taken in the process of set ting up a Fair Employment Prac tices"
  ],
